						<summary>

						<p>The inscription belongs to the reign of <hi rend="bold">Jagadēkamalla Jayasiṅghadēva II</hi> and registers the gift of land made by Dāmōdara-Śeṭṭi, after purchasing it from Maddimayya-Nāyaka, the <hi rend="italic">Ūroḍeya</hi> of <hi rend="bold">Lokkiguṇḍi,</hi> to the temples of <hi rend="bold">Traipurushadēva</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Bāraha-Nārāyaṇadēva</hi> (Twelve Nārāyaṇas). The father of Dāmōdara, <hi rend="bold">Perggaḍe Dhōyipayya,</hi> is stated to have constructed these temples and set up the <hi rend="italic">garuḍastambha</hi> therein. The inscription contains two dates, viz., <hi rend="bold">Śaka 959, Īśvara, Āshāḍha, śu. 5, Sunday</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Āśvayuja, amāvāsyā, solar eclipse, vyatīpāta,</hi> which respectively correspond to <hi rend="bold">A.D. 1037, June 20,</hi> (which was Monday and not Sunday), and <hi rend="bold">A.D. 1037, October 11, Tuesday.</hi></p>						

						<p>(Published in <hi rend="italic">Ep. Ind.</hi> Vol. XIX, pp. 217 ff).</p>						

						<p>The continuation of the inscription not published here reads thus:</p>						

						</summary>
